{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01Pbv3tKnMzN56FMCkJXekf2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_013Sv9Qga2eKPMw52hzE3JYb","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Required patient fields (name, date of birth, insurance ID) are validated before any downstream processing — missing fields produce a clear error listing all missing items.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is pure input validation logic with no external dependencies, I/O, or state. The validator is a single function that takes a patient object, checks field presence, and returns an error list. The failure boundary is entirely local: either the validation function checks all three fields or it doesn't. A mock or external system adds nothing — we're testing pure deterministic logic.","test_description":"Unit test calling the validator with missing fields (omit name, omit DOB, omit insurance ID, omit all three). Verify: (1) error message lists exactly the missing fields, (2) error message is clear and actionable, (3) validator doesn't proceed downstream for invalid input.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.95,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Date of birth validation rejects future dates, dates more than 150 years ago, and non-date strings.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Pure business logic validation with deterministic comparison. The function parses input, compares to a reference date (current time, which can be injected), and returns accept/reject. No external services, no I/O, no concurrency. The code either correctly implements the three rejection rules or it doesn't.","test_description":"Unit test with injected 'current date' parameter. Test cases: (1) future date (today+1, tomorrow, next year) — reject, (2) very old date (151+ years ago) — reject, (3) valid date (25 years ago) — accept, (4) non-date strings ('abc', '2025-13-45', empty string) — reject. Verify rejection reason is clear.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.98,"Integration":0.02,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The insurance eligibility check sends the correct patient ID and plan code to the payer API and correctly interprets the 'eligible' vs 'not eligible' vs 'pending' response.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A Unit test with a mocked HTTP client would verify that the code *constructs* a request correctly in isolation, but would miss real failures: wrong HTTP method (GET vs POST), wrong path, malformed headers, serialization bugs, or response parsing against real API shape. The actual failure boundary is at the HTTP contract layer. We need to wire up the HTTP client and mock the server to verify request construction *and* response parsing. This is integration: testing the HTTP client library's interaction with a mock server.","test_description":"Integration test using a mock HTTP server (e.g., Python `responses` library or Node.js `nock`). (1) Mock the payer API endpoint to respond with {status: 'eligible'}, (2) Call the eligibility check with a patient ID and plan code, (3) Assert the mock server received POST (or correct method) with correct path, headers, body format (JSON/XML/form-encoded), (4) Assert response parsing extracts 'eligible' status correctly. Repeat with 'not eligible' and 'pending' responses. Verify the code fails gracefully on malformed responses.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the payer API is unreachable, the system marks eligibility as 'pending' and continues the intake rather than blocking.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is error-handling logic in the HTTP path. A Unit test that passes a mock exception wouldn't catch the real failure: the code might not catch the actual exception type thrown by the HTTP library, might not set the right fallback state, or might silently fail. We need to simulate a real network failure (timeout, connection refused, DNS failure) and verify the error handling. Integration with a mock HTTP server (configured to fail) lets us test the actual error path.","test_description":"Integration test using mock HTTP server configured to simulate failure: (1) Mock server raises connection timeout or returns no response, (2) Call eligibility check, (3) Verify no exception is raised to caller, (4) Verify eligibility status is set to 'pending', (5) Verify the intake function continues (calls next step) instead of blocking. Test both timeout and connection refused scenarios.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The AI symptom triage correctly assigns high urgency to symptom combinations that indicate emergency conditions (e.g., chest pain + shortness of breath).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The behavior depends on what the *real AI medical reasoning engine* produces. A Unit test with a mocked model (returns hardcoded {urgency: 'high'}) always passes, even if the real model fails to recognize emergencies or misclassifies symptoms. The failure boundary is at the model itself: does it produce correct urgency judgments? We need to test against the real model (or a deterministic test set the model was validated on) to ensure it correctly identifies emergency patterns. This is inherently non-deterministic or training-data dependent, so we must use the real model.","test_description":"Agentic test calling the real triage service (or a fixed/deterministic version of the model if available). Provide a list of emergency symptom combinations (chest pain + SOB, severe abdominal pain + fever, etc.) and verify the model returns urgency='high' or equivalently high urgency score. If the model is non-deterministic, run multiple times and check success rate meets a threshold (e.g., 90%+). Verify both that the urgency is high AND that the model doesn't false-negative on known emergencies.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The symptom triage produces a natural language explanation of its urgency assessment that a clinician can review, not just a numeric score.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The core failure to catch is: 'the system returns only a score, no explanation field.' This is code/integration logic: given that the model returns an explanation, does the code include it in the output? A Unit test with a mocked response can verify the code correctly extracts and formats the explanation. However, Integration is safer because it tests the real service's response shape — the model might not return an explanation field at all, and Integration would catch that. The quality of the explanation itself (whether a clinician would actually understand it) depends on the real model, but the presence and format of the explanation is an integration contract.","test_description":"Integration test calling the triage service with test symptoms. Verify: (1) response includes an 'explanation' field (not null/empty), (2) explanation is a non-empty string of reasonable length (not a single word or truncated), (3) explanation is present *in addition to* a numeric urgency score (not instead of). Check that the explanation relates to the symptoms provided (spot-check readability).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.2,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"An appointment is scheduled in the first available slot that matches the assigned urgency level — high urgency gets same-day, medium gets within 48 hours.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This involves reading available slots from the calendar database and writing an appointment. A Unit test with a mocked calendar (always returns slots, always succeeds in writing) wouldn't catch real failures: wrong slot selection logic, database constraints, transaction isolation, or write failures. We need to test against a real or test calendar database to verify: (1) the code correctly filters slots by urgency and time window, (2) the appointment is actually persisted, (3) the selected slot is truly the first available.","test_description":"Integration test with a test calendar database. Set up: populate calendar with known available slots (e.g., 2 p.m. today, 10 a.m. tomorrow, 3 p.m. in 2 days). Schedule a high-urgency patient, verify appointment is at 2 p.m. today (same-day). Schedule a medium-urgency patient, verify it's booked within 48 hours (not today). Verify appointments are persisted in the database. Verify the code doesn't book slots outside the urgency window.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"The scheduling step does not double-book a time slot even when two patients are being processed concurrently.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is a race-condition test. A Unit test (even with a real mock calendar object) running single-threaded would pass even if the code has a race: read-check-write with no locking. A real failure: two concurrent requests both read 'slot available,' both proceed, both write an appointment to the same slot. To catch this, we need the *real calendar database's transaction/locking semantics* and *concurrent requests* issuing at the same time. This is integration: real database + concurrent threads.","test_description":"Integration test with real test calendar database and concurrency. Setup: one available slot (e.g., 2 p.m.). Spawn two concurrent threads/tasks both trying to schedule different patients for the same slot. Both call the scheduling function simultaneously (or with minimal delay). Assert: exactly one succeeds and writes the appointment, the other receives a 'no available slot' or 'conflict' error. Verify the database contains exactly one appointment, not two. Repeat 10+ times to catch intermittent race conditions.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.9,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"The confirmation message includes the patient name, appointment time, provider name, and preparation instructions appropriate to the visit type.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Formatting a message from multiple data sources requires integration: the code pulls patient data (from intake), appointment data (from calendar), provider data (lookup by appointment), and visit-type-specific instructions (lookup by visit type). A Unit test passing in all data as parameters would verify formatting but miss data-lookup failures. The real failure: appointment is written but provider name is wrong, or instructions don't match the visit type. Integration testing with a test database ensures the code correctly aggregates data from multiple sources and formats it.","test_description":"Integration test with test databases (patient records, calendar, provider directory, visit-type templates). Create a test patient, schedule an appointment with a specific provider and visit type (e.g., 'cardiology consultation'). Call the confirmation message function. Verify message includes: (1) correct patient name from intake, (2) correct appointment date/time from calendar, (3) correct provider name from directory, (4) appropriate preparation instructions for cardiology (not generic). Test with multiple visit types to ensure instructions vary correctly.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"The full intake pipeline — validate, check insurance, triage symptoms, schedule, confirm — completes for a real patient submission without manual intervention.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This is the full end-to-end pipeline with multiple steps: validate → call insurance API → call AI triage model → schedule in database → send confirmation. Each step has its own failure modes (validation error, API timeout, model failure, scheduling conflict, message failure) and the pipeline must handle them gracefully. A System test might call each service individually; a Workflow test orchestrates all steps together, verifies they execute in correct order, data flows correctly between steps, and the real AI model produces valid output. This tests the orchestration logic and integration of multiple agentic/external components in sequence.","test_description":"Workflow test with real/near-real dependencies (or well-mocked versions that simulate real behavior). Submit a complete intake form with valid patient data and symptoms. Verify: (1) validation passes, (2) insurance eligibility is checked and result is 'eligible' or 'pending' (not error), (3) triage returns a non-null urgency and explanation, (4) appointment is successfully scheduled (in calendar), (5) confirmation message is generated and includes all required fields, (6) entire flow completes without exception or manual step. Test edge case: patient with high urgency is scheduled same-day; pending insurance still allows intake to complete.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.68}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":14119,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":14119},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fd8b8df4-2178-4b71-982b-bb5cb9842023","uuid":"ad7ab19d-8783-4bc3-973b-6397960d5f29"}
